NO KIDDING!  Or if someone were to come to me and say &quot;Do you know
what a gerund is?&quot;  (I do, but I probably wouldn't be inclined to
tell them, if their intent was to approve or to &quot;out&quot; me or shame me
somehow.)

And I wouldn't ask another folksinger to explain to me in words what
kinds of music should end in unison on the last verse instead of a
chord, or to ask them which style needed WAY more thirds and fifths
and rarely any fourths (though sevenths are cool there).  And how
cruel would I be if the person had to say &quot;I have no idea what you're
talking about.&quot;  And what if the person just didn't know the
teminology but could harmonize like God or Emmylou Harris, so it was
really none of MY business anyway?

So maybe run a few scenarios like that in terms of your own knowledge
and see what emotions come up and that might help you shield and
fortify your child when similarly unreasonable requests are made of her.

Sandra
