My kids have a variety of ways of dealing with quizzing attempts.
Their most common response was, &quot;I don't really know much about that,
but do you know...&quot; and would to proceed to discuss something they had
recently discovered that was usually way beyond what kids do in school
(though not always.)  It inevitably would redirect the conversation.

Of course it would depend on the person who was doing the quizzing
(and which of my kids was responding.)  Even if they knew the answer,
sometimes they might just answer but more often than not they would
use the &quot;if you don't now, I'm not going to tell you,&quot; approach.
Jacob has been known to explain to people how they can find the
answer--but not answer the actually question.

When my then mother-in-law tried to quiz my oldest three on
multiplication tables, Jacob proceeded to explain the concept of
multiplication in his then 8-year-old understanding of the process.
He knew the concept, but did not have the tables memorized.  When she
persisted in trying to get him to tell her what 8X7 equals, he said,
&quot;But I just told you how to get the answer!  If you don't understand,
just use a calculator.&quot;  and walked away from her.

My oldest three are Kelsey, almost 16; Jacob, 14; and Kaleb, 13 now.
I haven't heard them getting quizzed in years.  Kelsey is the queen at
redirection.  Jacob has a way of turning things back at a person so
you feel like a fool.  Kaleb tends to just give a look of disgust.

Before she died this spring, Jossilyn (9) had strong similarities to
Jacob.  But she would often start with, &quot;Oh, I don't know that.  What
is the use of that? &quot;  and might launch into a discussion of what is
wrong with school and why she didn't like it there.  (Though she only
ever spent maybe 8 weeks in school when she was seven--at her
insistence.)  She liked to talk, that girl...  But she was also a big
fan of the look of disgust.

My youngest two are only 5 and 3, so they haven't experienced the
quizzing yet, but I tend to think they will receive less of it thanks
to the older kids.

I have also been known to run interference with quizzing.  I might
jump in with my own answer as if I was the one being asked (acting
like I thought they actually just wanted to know the answer.)  This
has worked well to redirect the conversation to me and then we can
have a discussion about quizzing and why it is rude and doesn't prove
anything.

There are any number of ways of dealing with this issue--some seem
more rude than others.  What works best for you and your daughter will
depend on you personalities.  It is important that you get past being
uncomfortable over what you child does NOT know and focus on what she
DOES know.

Hope this helps
Marge
